1. Linux Fundamentals

> Introduction to Linux:
    Understanding the Linux operating system, its architecture, and ecosystem

What is Linux?
  Open-source Unix-like operating system kernel created by Linus Torvalds in 1991
  Forms the base of many distributions (distros) like Ubuntu, Debian, CentOS, Fedora, Arch
  Powers servers, supercomputers, Android devices, and embedded systems
  Free to use, modify, and distribute under GPL license

Linux Architecture
  Kernel: Core component managing hardware, memory, processes, and system calls
  Shell: Command-line interface (bash, zsh, fish etc.) for user interaction
    - bash (Bourne Again SHell): The most widely used default shell; known for its versatility and script compatibility.
    - zsh (Z Shell): Highly customizable with advanced tab completion, globbing, and "Oh My Zsh" framework support.
    - fish (Friendly Interactive SHell): User-centric with syntax highlighting, autosuggestions, and a web-based configuration tool.
    - sh (Bourne Shell): The original Unix shell; minimalist and used primarily for basic system recovery and scripts.
    - ksh (KornShell): Combines features of the Bourne shell (sh) and C shell (csh); favored in enterprise and legacy Unix environments.
    - csh (C Shell): Uses syntax similar to the C programming language; 
    - dash (Debian Almquist Shell): A lightweight, POSIX-compliant shell used in Debian/Ubuntu for fast system booting.
  System Libraries: Provide functions for applications (glibc, etc.)
    - glibc (GNU Library for C): The essential wrapper for system calls; defines standard functions like open(), read(), and malloc().
    - musl: A lightweight, fast, and simple C library; often used in embedded systems or minimal distributions like Alpine Linux.
    - libstdc++: The standard C++ library; provides core functionality for applications written in C++.
    - openssl: Provides robust cryptographic functions and protocols (SSL/TLS) for secure communication and data encryption.
    - zlib: A foundational library for data compression used by many system tools and applications.
    - libpthread: Implements POSIX threads for multi-threaded application execution and management.
  System Utilities: Essential tools and programs (ls, cp, grep, etc.)
  Desktop Environment: Optional GUI layer (GNOME, KDE, XFCE)
    - GNOME: Focused on modern design, simplicity, and a workflow-oriented interface; default for many major distros.
    - KDE Plasma: Highly flexible and customizable; offers a traditional "Windows-like" layout with powerful integrated tools.
    - XFCE: Lightweight and stable; designed for performance and low resource usage without sacrificing functionality.
    - MATE: A continuation of the classic GNOME 2 interface; provides a traditional, intuitive desktop experience.
    - Cinnamon: Developed for Linux Mint; balances modern features with a traditional, familiar desktop layout.

Popular Distributions
  Ubuntu/Debian: User-friendly, large community, apt package manager
  CentOS/RHEL/Fedora: Enterprise-focused, yum/dnf package manager
  Arch Linux: Rolling release, minimal base, pacman package manager
  openSUSE: YaST configuration tool, zypper package manager

Key Differences from Windows
  Case-sensitive filesystem (File.txt â‰  file.txt)
  Forward slashes for paths (/home/user) vs backslashes (C:\Users)
  No drive letters - everything under root directory /
  Package managers instead of .exe installers
  Text-based configuration files in /etc instead of registry
