> Filesystem Hierarchy:
    Understanding Linux directory structure and file organization

Root Directory Structure
  / - Root directory, top of filesystem hierarchy
  /home - User home directories (/home/username)
  /root - Home directory for root user
  /etc - System configuration files
  /var - Variable data (logs, databases, web content)
  /usr - User programs and data (read-only)
  /bin - Essential user command binaries
  /sbin - System administration binaries
  /tmp - Temporary files (cleared on reboot)
  /opt - Optional third-party software
  /dev - Device files (hard drives, terminals)
  /proc - Virtual filesystem for process information
  /sys - Virtual filesystem for kernel/hardware info

File Types
  Regular files (-): Normal files containing data
  Directories (d): Folders containing other files
  Symbolic links (l): Shortcuts pointing to other files
  Character devices (c): Serial devices like terminals
  Block devices (b): Storage devices like hard drives
  Sockets (s): Inter-process communication
  Named pipes (p): FIFO special files

Permissions System
  Three permission types: read (r/4), write (w/2), execute (x/1)
  Three user categories: owner, group, others
  Example: -rwxr-xr-- means owner:rwx, group:r-x, others:r--
  chmod 755 file = rwxr-xr-x (owner full, others read+execute)
  chmod u+x file = add execute permission for owner
  chown user:group file = change owner and group
  Special permissions: SUID (4), SGID (2), Sticky bit (1)

Path Types
  Absolute path: Starts from root (/) - /home/user/documents/file.txt
  Relative path: From current directory - documents/file.txt or ../file.txt
  . represents current directory
  .. represents parent directory
  ~ represents user home directory
  - represents previous directory (cd -)
__________________________________________________________________________________________________________


> Essential Commands:
    Core commands for navigation and file manipulation

Navigation Commands
  pwd - Print working directory (shows current location)
  cd /path - Change directory to absolute path
  cd .. - Go up one directory level
  cd ~ or cd - Go to home directory
  cd - - Go to previous directory
  ls - List directory contents
  ls -l - Long format with permissions, owner, size, date
  ls -a - Show hidden files (starting with .)
  ls -lh - Human-readable file sizes (KB, MB, GB)
  ls -R - Recursive listing of subdirectories

File Operations
  touch file.txt - Create empty file or update timestamp
  mkdir directory - Create new directory
  mkdir -p path/to/dir - Create nested directories
  cp source dest - Copy file
  cp -r dir1 dir2 - Copy directory recursively
  mv source dest - Move or rename file/directory
  rm file - Delete file
  rm -r directory - Delete directory recursively
  rm -f file - Force delete without confirmation
  rmdir directory - Remove empty directory

Viewing File Content
  cat file - Display entire file content
  cat file1 file2 - Concatenate multiple files
  less file - View file with scrolling (q to quit)
  more file - View file page by page
  head file - Show first 10 lines
  head -n 20 file - Show first 20 lines
  tail file - Show last 10 lines
  tail -f file - Follow file updates in real-time (logs)
  wc file - Count lines, words, characters
  wc -l file - Count only lines

Search Commands
  find /path -name 'pattern' - Search files by name
  find . -type f -name '*.txt' - Find all .txt files
  find /home -user john - Find files owned by user
  find . -mtime -7 - Files modified in last 7 days
  locate filename - Fast search using database
  updatedb - Update locate database (run as root)
  which command - Show path of executable
  whereis command - Show binary, source, manual locations
